WorkItem.Description:
This is a great library, but I ran into an issue where greater than, less than fail for DateTime values.
 
            ExpressionContext ec = new ExpressionContext();
            ec.Variables.Add("o", new DateTime(2009, 4, 10) );
            IGenericExpression<bool> e = ec.CompileGeneric<bool>("o >= #04/08/2009#");
            Assert.IsTrue(e.Evaluate());
 
I had to get it working by using this syntax
 
            ExpressionContext ec = new ExpressionContext();
            ec.Variables.Add("o", new DateTime(2009, 4, 10));
            IGenericExpression<bool> e = ec.CompileGeneric<bool>("o.Year = 2009 And o.Month >= 4 And o.Day >= 8");
            Assert.IsTrue(e.Evaluate());

Comments.Message:
I think the problem is that, by default, date literals are interpreted as dd/MM/yyyy.  This makes #04/08/2009# become August 4, 2009.

If you change the format for date literals like so:
ExpressionContext ec = new ExpressionContext();
ec.ParserOptions.DateTimeFormat = "MM/dd/yyyy";

then the expression correctly evaluates to true.
